definition.value: Any of various disorders affecting libido.
A disorder characterized by sexual hyperactivity.
A disorder characterized by sexual hypoactivity, marked by sudden lack in sexual interest despite desire for sexual stimulation.
Any of various sexual disorders with primarily physiological causes.
A condition in which one has difficulty reaching the orgasm phase of sexual intercourse or reaching such a phase is considered not possible.

A disorder characterized by recurrent or persistent extreme aversion to, and avoidance of, all genital contact with a sexual partner. The aversion to sexual contact is not attributable to another psychiatric disorder.
Note that this disorder is considered separate from asexuality as a sexual orientation and that asexuality is not a diagnosis.

Sexual arousal disorder is characterized by a lack or absence of sexual fantasies and desire for sexual activity in a situation that would normally produce sexual arousal, or the inability to attain or maintain typical responses to sexual arousal.
Any of various syndromes primarily affecting the neurological system of the body.
A disorder characterized by sexual hyperactivity which is paraphilic in nature.
A disorder characterized by sexual hyperactivity which is not paraphilic in nature.
Behavior considered of an abnormal sexual nature and therefore likely clinically significant.
An act performed without delay, reflection, voluntary direction or obvious control in response to a stimulus.
Initiation of actions without forethought as to the cost, results or consequences.

The behavior of performing an act persistently and repetitively without it leading to reward or pleasure. The act is usually a small, circumscribed behavior, almost ritualistic, yet not pathologically disturbing. Examples of compulsive behavior include twirling of hair, checking something constantly, not wanting pennies in change, straightening tilted pictures, etc.
Compulsive behaviors considered sexual in nature.
Compulsive behaviors performed in quick succession ritualistically.
Compulsive sexual behavior that is paraphilic in nature.
Compulsive sexual behavior that is not paraphilic in nature.
Masturbatory behavior that is compulsive.
Nonparaphilic sexual behavior considered excessive.
Paraphilic sexual behavior considered excessive.
Any of various disorders affecting genital arousal.

Spontaneous, persistent, unwanted and uncontrollable genital arousal in the absence of sexual stimulation or sexual desire, and is typically not relieved by orgasm. Instead, multiple orgasms over hours or days may be required for relief.
Difficulty experienced by an individual or a couple during any stage of a normal sexual activity, including physical pleasure, desire, preference, arousal or orgasm.
Sexual dysfunction with a primarily non-physiological cause.
Sexual dysfunction with a primarily physiological cause.
A dysfunction involving erection.
A dysfunction involving ejaculation.
Low sexual drive considered unhealthy or otherwise nonnormative.
A dysfunction involving orgasm.
Any sexual disorder which causes persistent pain relating specifically to sexual intercourse or other sexual activity.
A dysfunction of the urogenital system.
Recurrent or persistent involuntary spasm of the outer muscles of the vagina, occurring during vaginal penetration.
Sexual relationship disorder is a disorder where a person has difficulties in forming or maintaining a sexual relationship because of their gender identity and/or sexual orientation.
Developmental disorders with primarily psychosexual symptoms.
Sexual maturation disorder is a disorder of anxiety or depression related to an uncertainty about one's gender identity and/or sexual orientation.

Note that neither sexual orientation or gender identity are considered in and of themselves disorders; in this sense, sexual maturation disorder could be considered culturally bound within societies which mistreat sexual and gender minorities. Further, sexual maturation disorder is, by definition, different from ego-dystonic sexual orientation wherein sexual orientation or gender identity is repressed or otherwise denied.
Behavior patterns of persons using contraception or in their specific use of contraception.
Any of various attributes of an organism or other biological material.

Physical or behavioral traits of an organism (typically of a sexually dimorphic organism) which are often, but not always, indicative of its biological sex (i.e. whether the organism produces male or female gametes).
Sex characteristics that are congenital.
Sex characteristics that are acquired after birth, typically during puberty or related processes.
The state in which a secondary sex characteristic or characteristics doesn't develop.
a physiological phenomenon in which the erectile tissue (the penis or the clitoris) becomes enlarged and firm.
The expulsion of fluid from the genital area.
A physiological phenomenon where the clitoris becomes enlarged and firm.
A spontaneous erection of the clitoris during sleep or when waking up.
A spontaneous erection of the penis during sleep or when waking up.
An expulsion of fluid from or near the vagina during or before an orgasm.

The second stage of ejaculation during which orgasm occurs and the bulbospongiosus muscle squeezes strongly continuously, forcing semen to move from the ejaculatory ducts into the urethra. Following this, semen is pushed along the urethra until it shoots out of the end of the penis in spurts.
Any sort of ejaculatory behavior or process considered unhealthy or otherwise nonnormative.
Inability to ejaculate, usually for pathological reasons.
